Studsvik 6 MeV van de Graaff with
pulsed ion source, beam pulse width at half-height
is about 10 nanosec. At 1 MHz/s.
.Present experiment carried out with beam pulse width
at half-height of 2 nanosec. using a klystron bunching
system. Mean target current 1.5 microA.
T(p,n) reaction for E(n) less than 4.6 MeV,
total energy spread = +- 50 keV.
Length of gas target cell = 3 cm,  nickel foil
thickness = 2.5 milli-g/cm2.
The total neutron energy spread
Natural, cylinder of 5.0 cm height, 2.5 cm outer diam.
and 0.95 cm inner diam. Sample purity 99.5%.
Time of flight path = 300 cm.
.Target-scatterer distance = 10 cm,
scatterer-detector distance = 300 cm.
.Angular distributions measured in an angular interval
from 30 to 60 deg at E(n) up to 4.56 MeV, and from 20
to 160 deg above that energy,
data were collected in steps of 10 deg. except in the
extreme forward angles where measurements were made at
5 deg.
Neutron TOF detector, scintillator NE102A
and size 10 cm diam., 5 cm length,
photomultiplier RCA 7264,
spectrometer time resolution  3 nanosec.
.The relative n-detector efficiency was obtained by
observation of the n-p scattering at some energies by
detecting the number of neutrons scattered in differ-
ent angles at a constant primary neutron energy. The
efficiency function showed to be linear between 2.5
and 7 MeV, and an extrapolation to 8 MeV possible.
Neutron flux monitoring, direction sensitive
fast neutron monitor (long counter monitor).
From A.Horsley (J,Nucl.Data.2A(1966)243).
Polythene scatterer 3 cm in height, 0.95 cm outer and
0.65 cm inner diameter.

x4freetext: Corrections for neutron multiple scattering in the
sample material, geometry effects from the target
sample-detector system, and neutron flux attenuation
in the sample.
Uncertainties in cr. sect. are mainly due to
the uncertainties of the estimates of the peak areas
because of insufficient resolution in the time spectra
Total error. Including all sources the total
error can be conservatively estimated to be 15%.
For the inelastic cross sections corresponding to the
at 4.56 MeV neutron energy the errors are about 30%,
and even about 50 % in two cases, i.e. for neutron
groups to the weakly excited levels at 2.545 and
2.790 MeV, owing to low counting statistics in the
peaks besides the insufficient time resolution.
